<sn><md>### Formation Process

1. **Magma Generation:** Occurs deep within Earth due to `high temperature, pressure, and mantle processes` causes partial metling of exisiting rocks.
2. **Cooling and Solidification:**
   * `Slow` cooling **inside Earth** forms `coarse`-grained rocks.
   * `Rapid` cooling **on the surface** forms `fine`-grained or glassy rocks.
3. **Crystallization:** Minerals crystallize at different temperatures, giving unique textures.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Facts

* Nearly all `continental and oceanic crust` originally formed from igneous processes.
* Common minerals include `quartz, feldspar, micas, amphiboles, pyroxenes, and olivine`.
* Texture depends entirely on `cooling rate`, not composition.
* Large crystals → slow cooling (intrusive).
* Small or no crystals → rapid cooling (extrusive).
* Igneous rocks `never contain fossils` because high temperature destroys organic remains.
* Widely used as building stones due to hardness and resistance to weathering.</md></sn><sn><md>#### Based on Mode of Formation

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Intrusive {.text-center}
Plutonic or Continental <br>
Form inside the Earth from `slow cooling magma`.<br>
Characteristics:
* Large, visible crystals
* Coarse-grained texture

Examples: `Granite`, Diorite, Gabbro
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Extrusive{.text-center}
Volacanic  or Oceanic<br>
Form on the surface from `rapid cooling lava`.<br>
Characteristics:
* Fine-grained or glassy texture
* Small crystals

Examples: `Basalt`, Rhyolite, Andesite, Obsidian, Pumice
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Based on Chemical Composition

| Category            | Silica Content    | Color         | Density   | Key Characteristics                                      | Examples          |
| ------------------- | ----------------- | ------------- | --------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------- |
| **Felsic (Acidic)** | High (65%+)       | Light-colored | Low       | Rich in quartz &amp; feldspar                                | Granite, Rhyolite |
| **Intermediate**    | Moderate (55–65%) | Medium color  | Moderate  | Balanced mix of light &amp; dark minerals                    | Diorite, Andesite |
| **Mafic (Basic)**   | Low (45–55%)      | Dark-colored  | High      | Rich in iron, magnesium; heavy minerals                  | Gabbro, Basalt    |
| **Ultramafic**      | Very low (&lt;45%)   | Very dark     | Very high | Very rich in iron &amp; magnesium; almost no silica minerals | Peridotite        |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Based on Texture

| Texture Type                    | Crystal Size            | Cooling Rate                     | Key Characteristics                              | Examples             |
| ------------------------------- | ----------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ | -------------------- |
| **Coarse-Grained (Phaneritic)** | Large, visible crystals | Slow cooling                     | Forms deep inside Earth; well-developed minerals | Granite              |
| **Fine-Grained (Aphanitic)**    | Microscopic crystals    | Rapid cooling                    | Forms on surface; smooth, fine texture           | Basalt               |
| **Glassy**                      | No crystals             | Extremely rapid cooling          | Lava cools too fast for crystals to form         | Obsidian             |
| **Vesicular**                   | Contains pores/holes    | Rapid cooling with trapped gases | Gas bubbles preserved in the rock                | Pumice, Scoria       |
| **Porphyritic**                 | Mixed crystal sizes     | Two-stage cooling                | Large phenocrysts embedded in fine matrix        | Porphyritic Andesite |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Examples of Common Igneous Rocks

